1
00:00:00,541 --> 00:00:05,791
Rice and broth, they brought it ready in foam plates

2
00:00:06,250 --> 00:00:09,625
In the morning they brought us tahini and <i>sammoun</i> [bread roll]

3
00:00:09,666 --> 00:00:12,125
And sometimes they brought pieces of cheese with it

4
00:00:12,916 --> 00:00:15,541
That was in the morning, and at night they brought dinner

5
00:00:16,833 --> 00:00:19,250
Interviewer: Did they bring rice and broth daily?

6
00:00:20,250 --> 00:00:24,250
They varied it—it wasn’t the same food every day

7
00:00:25,125 --> 00:00:27,791
Interviewer: How many pieces of <i>sammoun</i> did they bring per day? Witness: Two in the morning

8
00:00:28,791 --> 00:00:33,541
At noon, one piece with a plate of rice and a cup of broth

9
00:00:34,041 --> 00:00:36,250
Interviewer: So they didn’t mix them together?
Witness: No

10
00:00:36,291 --> 00:00:37,291
Interviewer: And what about dinner?

11
00:00:37,541 --> 00:00:43,916
At dinner they sometimes brought <i>sammoun</i> and cooked chicken

12
00:00:44,916 --> 00:00:48,166
They gave us the leg of the chicken, or the wing, or something else

13
00:00:48,666 --> 00:00:51,166
Interviewer: Was the food enough?
Witness: Yes, it was enough

14
00:00:51,541 --> 00:00:55,875
When a person is in prison, he won’t crave food because of the worry

15
00:00:57,291 --> 00:00:59,791
Interviewer: Tell me honestly, was it enough? Witness: Yes, it was fine

16
00:01:00,416 --> 00:01:03,666
Interviewer: Was the quality good or bad? Witness: It was bad

17
00:01:06,125 --> 00:01:07,541
Interviewer: Did it come hot or cold?

18
00:01:07,833 --> 00:01:10,375
They brought it sometimes hot and at other times cold

19
00:01:10,875 --> 00:01:12,041
Meaning they brought it from far away

20
00:01:12,666 --> 00:01:16,375
Interviewer: Did it ever happen that they asked you what you like to eat?

21
00:01:16,416 --> 00:01:17,666
No, they didn’t ask me

22
00:01:18,958 --> 00:01:20,916
If a person wanted to buy food

23
00:01:22,375 --> 00:01:25,291
He would tell the jailer he craved food from outside

24
00:01:25,375 --> 00:01:26,375
Like kebab or something else

25
00:01:27,250 --> 00:01:29,000
When the market was open

26
00:01:30,041 --> 00:01:31,625
They would bring us from the guy called Hazem

27
00:01:31,625 --> 00:01:33,416
I twice asked to buy kebab from him

28
00:01:33,833 --> 00:01:35,000
Half a portion for one person

29
00:01:35,125 --> 00:01:36,375
Two skewers were enough for me, two pieces

30
00:01:37,375 --> 00:01:41,250
Interviewer: When you sent someone to buy food or what you needed

31
00:01:41,375 --> 00:01:44,125
Was the ISIS member you sent

32
00:01:44,416 --> 00:01:47,000
Bargaining with you to take an amount of money in return for that?

33
00:01:47,125 --> 00:01:50,541
I would tell him, If you’re hungry, get yourself food with mine

34
00:01:50,625 --> 00:01:52,000
And he would say to me, No, they don’t accept that

35
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:56,958
Interviewer: Did he take an amount above the price of what he brought?

36
00:01:57,000 --> 00:01:58,375
No, he brought it at the same price

37
00:01:58,875 --> 00:02:02,375
Interviewer: Didn’t it happen sometimes that someone asked you for a bribe?

38
00:02:02,375 --> 00:02:03,375
No, not at all

39
00:02:03,541 --> 00:02:05,666
Interviewer: For example to connect you with your family by a phone call

40
00:02:05,750 --> 00:02:08,125
No, but sometimes I would send him to my house

41
00:02:08,166 --> 00:02:09,416
To bring me medicine

42
00:02:09,833 --> 00:02:14,000
That happened twice—I sent him to bring me medicine

43
00:02:14,875 --> 00:02:16,166
And his name was Abu Taha

44
00:02:18,541 --> 00:02:19,541
Interviewer: Who is this Abu Taha?

45
00:02:19,875 --> 00:02:21,666
He is one of their members

46
00:02:22,125 --> 00:02:24,125
Interviewer: Did you know him before? Witness: No

47
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:26,375
Interviewer: And when he did that

48
00:02:26,375 --> 00:02:28,375
By going to your house to bring you the medicine

49
00:02:28,375 --> 00:02:29,416
It was a kind act from him

50
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:33,375
Interviewer: Did he do that on their orders or on his own?

51
00:02:33,375 --> 00:02:37,750
No, on his own. Wasn’t he the jailer responsible for the room?

52
00:02:37,791 --> 00:02:40,666
During his shift I would ask him to go, because he knew the house, it was nearby

53
00:02:41,125 --> 00:02:42,958
Anyone from the street could have gone to bring it for me

54
00:02:43,541 --> 00:02:46,875
I used Angised and Isordil, heart medications

55
00:02:46,958 --> 00:02:49,625
Interviewer: In this case, did your family know you were detained?

56
00:02:49,875 --> 00:02:51,666
But they didn’t know in which place exactly

57
00:02:52,041 --> 00:02:54,041
Interviewer: So he didn’t tell them your location?
Witness: No, he didn’t tell them

58
00:02:54,500 --> 00:02:56,416
Interviewer: During your 28 days

59
00:02:56,541 --> 00:02:59,750
Did you need a doctor, or for a nurse to come to you?

60
00:02:59,791 --> 00:03:00,958
Did a doctor actually visit you?

61
00:03:00,958 --> 00:03:03,500
No, I know what I suffer from

62
00:03:04,125 --> 00:03:05,291
And the treatment I take

63
00:03:06,250 --> 00:03:07,875
Interviewer: Regardless of your knowledge of what you suffer from

64
00:03:07,875 --> 00:03:10,750
Did their schedule include a doctor visiting you from time to time?

65
00:03:10,791 --> 00:03:13,541
Yes, they asked us if we needed a doctor

66
00:03:13,541 --> 00:03:14,625
So they could take us to him

67
00:03:15,125 --> 00:03:19,666
If you felt your blood pressure was high, for example, or something like that

68
00:03:20,500 --> 00:03:24,833
But I didn’t ask them for this

69
00:03:25,541 --> 00:03:28,375
Interviewer: You mean there was understanding of your health condition

70
00:03:28,375 --> 00:03:29,791
And special consideration for you

71
00:03:29,875 --> 00:03:30,875
Yes, they knew that

72
00:03:31,791 --> 00:03:33,041
Interviewer: Regarding the food

73
00:03:33,125 --> 00:03:37,125
Was there any kind that harmed you and they still brought it to you?

74
00:03:37,125 --> 00:03:39,125
Or did they not bring it to you because you told them it harmed you?

75
00:03:39,833 --> 00:03:42,250
No, the food they brought didn’t harm me

76
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:45,375
If there was fat, I wouldn’t eat it

77
00:03:46,166 --> 00:03:48,541
For example, I would eat the bread and the chicken thigh

78
00:03:49,291 --> 00:03:50,375
And I wouldn’t eat the rest

79
00:03:50,375 --> 00:03:52,250
Because I suffered from high blood lipids, and until now

80
00:03:52,250 --> 00:03:54,625
Interviewer: Didn’t it happen one day that they asked you

81
00:03:54,666 --> 00:03:57,041
About this food, whether it was beneficial or harmful to you?

82
00:03:57,041 --> 00:03:59,041
And did they try to bring you something that would help you and not harm you?

83
00:03:59,125 --> 00:04:01,625
They asked me, and I told them this doesn’t harm me

84
00:04:02,375 --> 00:04:04,125
Interviewer: So they asked you?
Witness: Yes, they asked me

85
00:04:04,541 --> 00:04:07,875
Interviewer: Do you think you had some kind of special care in the prison?

86
00:04:08,291 --> 00:04:09,375
Not like the treatment of others

87
00:04:09,416 --> 00:04:11,916
Interviewer: Considering they placed you in a place by yourself

88
00:04:11,958 --> 00:04:13,250
It was like that somewhat

89
00:04:13,875 --> 00:04:15,041
Interviewer: Was that because of your age?

90
00:04:15,041 --> 00:04:19,875
Or because they expected you would be with them and help them

91
00:04:19,916 --> 00:04:20,916
Yes, it was for that reason

92
00:04:22,041 --> 00:04:25,541
Meaning because they needed me, and they wanted me to join them

93
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,625
This good treatment, they wanted from it in return

94
00:04:28,666 --> 00:04:32,916
To motivate you and urge you to join them

95
00:04:32,958 --> 00:04:34,041
Yes, it was like that

96
00:04:34,291 --> 00:04:36,833
Interviewer: Is that it?
Witness: Yes, I felt that
